@DavidMS51 - the old `pixel` method could be simulated by creating (and holding onto) a blank 8x8 Pillow image, and then calling any number of `image.putpixel((x, y), 1)` to set pixels followed by `device.display(image)`. 

To blank out a pixel: `image.putpixel((x, y), 0)` followed by `device.display(image)`.

See http://pillow.readthedocs.io/en/4.3.x/reference/Image.html#PIL.Image.Image.putpixel

@nicholasserra Would you like me to try to rewrite this as a parameter to `toc`, like `-x toc={toc}` where the final TOC HTML would replace the value of the parameter (`{toc}`) allowing the user control over the placement without imposing any preferences on them?

I gave another thought to prepending and I don't really see anyone using it that way, so I think more control is necessary for this to make sense and I think providing a solution that utilizes substitution would make this functionality flexible enough for most use cases.

I still don't know how to tackle the fact that the TOC HTML will contain all the headings, including the ones the precede it in the document if user places it into a nested section (like *{title}* > *Table of Contents*). I think this is a hard problem. We can just drop first level headings (or only the first one) but some people start their documents with level-3 headings because of the rendered output heading size (yep...), some people have multiple first-level headings which also doesn't jive well with this… A lot of variation. We could track which headings come before the substitution string (the value of the `toc` extra) and only render those after it. Many variations and I think it's important to try and avoid being too smart for theoretical benefit, so in the end I think the best solution is to leave the TOC structure as is and just dump it there. Having main title and the TOC section title in the TOC itself in exchange for the ability to place the TOC to one's liking is I think the right tradeoff.

