@matt-gardner @tusharkhot PyHocon interprets environment variables as strings.  However, `--overrides` simply allows you to write PyHocon, so you can control the type of what you are overriding.  If you write something like `--overrides "trainer.cuda_device=$FOO_ENV` then it will be a numeric value as it's unquoted (whereas `--overrides "trainer.cuda_device="$FOO_ENV"` would be a string).

Note I'm not advocated for the above--just articulating how it works.

I'm not terribly excited about methods like `pop_int` to interpret environment variables, as we would end up writing custom parsing code and we could make assumptions that might not always be true (what if the users wants a string with an integer value?).  

